                    <figure>
                    <img class="single" src="../images/articles/plasma-peratt-environment/pl_peratt_indian_graphic_numbers.jpeg" alt="Courtesy of the TX Archaeological Research Laboratory, U of Texas at Austin." /><figcaption>Courtesy of the TX Archaeological Research Laboratory, U of Texas at Austin.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>
                <h5 class="figure-title">Figure 9</h5>

                <h2 class="section-title" id="colluvium"><span>Colluvium</span></h2>
                <p class="article-p">The geology of Sardinia can not be explained without acknowledging plasma’s role. The sculpting of the landscape is too precise to have been a violent event. While electricity distorts the rock around the current’s path, figure 12, with a series of arching fractures, plasma makes clean slices leaving adjacent rock unaltered. This can be seen in figure 10 and 11. In figure 10, the light colored wedge of colluvium indicates it originally occupied this field. A plasma event sliced through it leaving a darker colluvium behind. The bedrock in figure 11 abruptly ends and was replaced with friable soil. Both are illustrative of a very precise flow of energy. The plasma boundary is very different from a pattern left by electricity.</p>
                
                <div class = "figure-margin d-grid article-col1-col1 center ">
                    <figure>
                        <img class="figure" src="../images/articles/plasma-peratt-environment/pl_plasma pattern2.jpeg" alt="Plasma sliced through colluvium. " class="plasma-pattern2"/><figcaption>Plasma sliced through colluvium. </figcaption>
                    <h5 class="figure-title">Figure 10</h5>

                    </figure>

                    <figure>
                        <img class="figure" src="../images/articles/plasma-peratt-environment/pl_plasma pattern3.jpeg" alt="Plasma sliced through the rock. " class="plasma-pattern3" /><figcaption>Plasma sliced through the rock. </figcaption>
                    <h5 class="figure-title">Figure 11</h5>

                    </figure>
                </div>

                <p class="article-p">Surrounding a current of electricity is an intense magnetic field. The field’s effect on rock is to discolor it, i.e. alter the molecular structure of the rock<a href="#fn5" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref5"><sup>5</sup></a>, and to fracture it as seen in figure 12. Less powerful electrical strikes discolor the rock without leaving evidence of fracturing. Sardinia makes very clear that electricity played a very insignificant role in shaping the island’s landscape.</p>
                
                <div class = "d-grid article-col1 center ">
                    <figure>
                        <img class="single" src="../images/articles/plasma-peratt-environment/pl_electrical_pattern.jpeg" alt="Curved fracturing of rock from the passage of an electrical current." /><figcaption>Curved fracturing of rock from the passage of an electrical current.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>
                <h5 class="figure-title">Figure 12</h5>


                <p class="article-p">Graphics on the walls of the Domus de Janas’ provide a detailed description of what occurred on Sardinia and what has been happening on the planet. As the z-pinch auroras became more energized, they progressed from red auroras, to Sipsey Events, to Peratt Events, to Castangia Structures. It was probably the latter that was responsible, at the end of the Pleistocene, for printing most of the complex mosaic pattern on the landscape around Gesico. As the first article pointed out, a <strong>vast</strong> amount of rock disappeared on Sardinia. The question is what happened to it? In all probability, the rock reverted to plasma. It is possible solid matter is another form of plasma. Another question the DdJs answer is the origin of gravity. There is a vast amount of evidence that rock was levitated on Sardinia. The only change on the island that could have accounted for the levitation was the presence over the island of z-pinches. As Dr. Peratt said one form of plasma exerts the same inverse proportional force as gravity. Therefore, plasma has to be the source of gravity.</p>
                
